I'm here with Aldo Ribello, who is a former minister of the Chamber of Deputies, former minister of defense, former minister of sport, current presidential candidate for the Christian Democracy Party.

06:50.000 --> 06:56.000
Although there's some controversies I want to talk about there, but you've had an illustrious history.

06:56.000 --> 06:59.000
You are a cornerstone of Brazilian politics.

06:59.000 --> 07:06.000
You are currently running against Lula and Bolsonaro, but in many ways you kind of exist at the intersection between both.

07:06.000 --> 07:13.000
You are kind of the almost Plato's philosopher king of Brazilian politics over the last 20 or 30 years.

07:13.000 --> 07:18.000
So I'm very excited to speak to you about your philosophy of Brazilian sovereignty.

07:18.000 --> 07:20.000
You're a long career.

07:20.000 --> 07:31.000
But the reason that I am here, as you know, I focus on kind of anomalous phenomena, the nature of reality, is that you tweeted something very interesting.

07:31.000 --> 07:35.000
You said as former defense minister, I am provoked to speak on the subject.

07:35.000 --> 07:36.000
You're talking about UFOs.

07:36.000 --> 07:39.000
I know what the armed forces have in their archives.

07:39.000 --> 07:47.000
What I can say is that if the US government reveals its documents, I will do the same if I am elected president of Brazil.

07:47.000 --> 07:50.000
So I'm very excited to be here.

07:50.000 --> 07:51.000
Thank you for having me.

07:51.000 --> 07:52.000
It's an honor.

07:52.000 --> 07:54.000
Thank you so much, Jesse.

07:54.000 --> 07:55.000
And welcome.

07:55.000 --> 07:56.000
Welcome to Brazil.

07:56.000 --> 07:59.000
I know it's your first time here in my country.

07:59.000 --> 08:00.000
So welcome.

08:00.000 --> 08:06.000
I hope that your stay does justice to you, not only as a journalist, but also as a guest.

08:06.000 --> 08:15.000
What was the first time, if you can recall, that you started to take UFOs more seriously?

08:15.000 --> 08:19.000
Was there a moment, do you remember, when you first heard about UFOs?

08:19.000 --> 08:41.000
Yes, in my youth, there was this huge curiosity about these phenomena, and it was a type of healthy curiosity, because the news was divided between phenomena that were observed, and there was also sci-fi literature that used this subject matter as the object of writers, journalists, and also aficionados.

08:41.000 --> 08:52.000
So it got all of our attention, and we saw that in the movies, in literature, and yeah, it got my attention.

08:52.000 --> 09:05.000
I've never monitored it really closely, but I've always been curious about seeing it in the news, especially with regards to phenomena that is related to national defense concerns.

09:05.000 --> 09:17.000
In Brazil alone, there are hundreds of episodes, but three at least were closely overseen by the armed forces and the Brazilian intelligence and defense systems.

09:17.000 --> 09:34.000
One occurred in the state of Pará, in the 70s, another one was in the 80s, in a town called São José dos Campos, and the other one was in the 90s, in the south of Minas Gerais, in the town of Varginha.

09:34.000 --> 09:46.000
These episodes were documented, were overseen, the armed forces were interested in the subject, because there was a concern that these events could pose a risk to national defense and security.

09:46.000 --> 10:03.000
And naturally, this, for me, someone who's always been concerned with issues pertaining to national security and national defense, as also part of Brazil's foreign policy.

10:03.000 --> 10:09.000
This is what led me to keep up with at least these three events.

10:09.000 --> 10:13.000
Hmm, I'm very excited to talk about all three events.

10:13.000 --> 10:18.000
I want to start with Prado, Operation Prado in 1977, Calares.

10:18.000 --> 10:30.000
It's a fascinating case, and it's a very dark case, because you have the people in this village, this little fishing village, were being terrorized, essentially.

10:30.000 --> 10:35.000
They called it the Chupa Chupa, because their blood was being extracted.

10:35.000 --> 10:39.000
The mayor was in deep fear.

10:39.000 --> 10:48.000
You had men and women sleeping in 50 to 60, you know, in one place, just so, you know, the men could defend the women.

10:48.000 --> 10:57.000
Because often it was younger females that were the targets of these sorts of attacks, and it felt like lasers and directed energy were being beamed at them.

10:57.000 --> 11:06.000
So, what do you know about this, and what do you know about this specifically that the rest of the public might not know?

11:06.000 --> 11:14.000
Well, Jesse, what all of us who keep up with this phenomena know is what has been documented, and there's a lot of it.

11:14.000 --> 11:25.000
Because there is testimony of the military who were in charge of the operation, because they had to send a whole task force to monitor these phenomena.

11:25.000 --> 11:40.000
And there are accounts of not only military, but also a physician, a doctor, who attended to the victims of these incursions, of these strange, unidentified beings.

11:40.000 --> 11:46.000
At night, they would see those objects in flight, and the method never varied.

11:46.000 --> 11:54.000
As it was flying, the object would cast down a beam of light, that light illuminated the person and paralyzed them.

11:54.000 --> 12:05.000
From in that white light came a second beam, which was yellowish in color and roughly 30 cm in diameter, that would be pointed at the person's chest.

12:05.000 --> 12:09.000
After that, there was another beam that was red.

12:09.000 --> 12:12.000
This beam would make a puncture.

12:12.000 --> 12:20.000
It extracted blood and also put something in the body of the victim, something like an implant.

12:20.000 --> 12:23.000
There were several deaths.

12:23.000 --> 12:30.000
So there's a suspicion that they were laser beams.

12:30.000 --> 12:35.000
But no one really knows what kind of beam struck and affected those people.

12:35.000 --> 12:42.000
And after being hit, these people had perforations, blood loss, they were anemic.

12:42.000 --> 12:45.000
They also suffered other…

12:45.000 --> 12:48.000
They felt numbness in their bodies.

12:48.000 --> 12:57.000
A number of injuries that were identified by the physician who assisted these people.

12:57.000 --> 13:12.000
And the officers who witnessed it and set up the whole operation in this village, in the state of Pará, documented these objects as they were approaching.

13:12.000 --> 13:14.000
And they couldn't identify where they were.

13:14.000 --> 13:17.000
So, that has been fully documented.

13:17.000 --> 13:23.000
Now, part of the reports and accounts of this event and the operation,

13:23.000 --> 13:30.000
I mean, it was a long operation, still remains classified,

13:30.000 --> 13:36.000
kept by the armed forces.

13:36.000 --> 13:43.000
But that which has been documented is substantial evidence of the existence of the phenomena,

13:43.000 --> 13:51.000
of the people that were victims of the contact with these unidentified objects,

13:51.000 --> 13:58.000
and accounts by highly credible people.

13:58.000 --> 14:04.000
These are officers from the armed forces and the physician who tended to these patients,

14:04.000 --> 14:10.000
who had complications and injuries that stemmed from the event that took place in the state of Pará.

14:10.000 --> 14:18.000
And you had an official investigation that it sort of prompted.

14:18.000 --> 14:21.000
It was, you know, Operation Prado.

14:21.000 --> 14:27.000
And you had Captain Holanda Lima go in and investigate.

14:27.000 --> 14:28.000
He brought a whole team.

14:28.000 --> 14:31.000
They documented 300 plus encounters.

14:31.000 --> 14:37.000
They took 500 photographs and they recorded 15 hours of Super 8 film footage.

14:37.000 --> 14:41.000
And they had a whole documentation that was over 2,000 pages.

14:41.000 --> 14:47.000
He himself actually saw an alien being that was in a space suit.

14:47.000 --> 14:50.000
And the being sort of gave him a hug.

14:50.000 --> 14:56.000
And he went on record about this later, about two decades later in 1997.

14:56.000 --> 15:00.000
And then he sadly committed suicide a few months after that.

15:01.000 --> 15:03.000
The Super 8 footage.

15:03.000 --> 15:08.000
This is still, I believe, exists in the defense ministry.

15:08.000 --> 15:09.000
Did you ever see it?

15:09.000 --> 15:12.000
And do you have access to it?

15:13.000 --> 15:22.000
Jesse, there is no question that there was an official operation executed by the Brazilian Armed Forces to monitor this phenomenon.

15:22.000 --> 15:26.000
With the title, Operation Prado.

15:26.000 --> 15:29.000
So, this isn't up for debate.

15:29.000 --> 15:31.000
The operation took place.

15:31.000 --> 15:39.000
It was an official operation led by the Armed Forces to monitor these phenomena in the state of Pará.

15:39.000 --> 15:49.000
The second fact is the existence of the diagnosis and the testimony of the physician regarding the victims that were affected by the same phenomena.

15:49.000 --> 15:54.000
There is no question about that either.

15:54.000 --> 16:04.000
The only question that still remains is about a report that was not documented or disclosed.

16:04.000 --> 16:11.000
On part of the then-captain, who later became a colonel, when he passed, he was a retired colonel.

16:11.000 --> 16:17.000
That part of the report, which is still classified, which remains confidential,

16:17.000 --> 16:29.000
is what we didn't have a chance to analyze or witness what it's comprised of.

16:29.000 --> 16:32.000
So, we only have access to that which has already been disclosed.

16:32.000 --> 16:45.000
And it's a full detailed description of the contact, the testimonials, and the testimony of the members of the armed forces that were responsible for leading the operation.

16:45.000 --> 16:48.000
So, there's no doubt about that.

16:48.000 --> 16:56.000
Now, you seem like a very thoughtful person who doesn't just take in evidence that's anomalous and not think about it a lot.

16:56.000 --> 17:01.000
Do you have any leading theories about what Kolaris was?

17:01.000 --> 17:04.000
Because it's such a bizarre fact pattern.

17:04.000 --> 17:07.000
You had puncture wounds, blood taken.

17:07.000 --> 17:11.000
It almost looked like ultraviolet burns on a lot of people.

17:11.000 --> 17:23.000
You had a physician who was present, actually, Dr. Carvalho, who famously went on record seeing two women who basically had strokes, who died due to these UFO contact events.

17:23.000 --> 17:27.000
Do you have any theories as to what caused all of this?

17:27.000 --> 17:34.000
There's a list of injuries, and all of this is part of the diagnosis of the medical report.

17:34.000 --> 17:40.000
It wasn't just a matter of the strokes or anemia or blood loss.

17:40.000 --> 17:57.000
Other consequences, like numbness, and a variety of others, that resulted from the contact of these people with these unidentified objects and beings.

17:57.000 --> 18:05.000
You see, I don't have the scientific knowledge.

18:05.000 --> 18:09.000
I was not present during the event.

18:09.000 --> 18:17.000
In order to develop a theory regarding the origin of whatever it was that was reported.

18:17.000 --> 18:26.000
Not only in this event that happened in Kolaris, but the others as well, like in Varginha.

18:26.000 --> 18:42.000
And if science itself, with all of its resources, all of its means, can't clarify, I think it would be reckless on my part in trying to develop my own theory on the origin of these phenomena.

18:42.000 --> 18:52.000
It really wouldn't be prudent of me to even attempt to provide a diagnostic after decades of efforts from experts and scientists and people who dedicated their whole lives,

18:52.000 --> 19:00.000
like Nick Pope himself, who went to his grave saying, well, I can't account for the 8% of the facts.

19:00.000 --> 19:04.000
Who am I to say anything?

19:04.000 --> 19:06.000
Fair enough.

19:06.000 --> 19:11.000
You know, Jacques Bellet is one of the godfathers of UFO research.

19:11.000 --> 19:12.000
He's French.

19:12.000 --> 19:13.000
He's an astronomer.

19:13.000 --> 19:16.000
He was actually involved in the invention of the internet.

19:16.000 --> 19:21.000
And he came down to Kolaris to investigate.

19:21.000 --> 19:26.000
His diaries are called Forbidden Science.

19:26.000 --> 19:37.000
And he came to the conclusion because he spoke to Dr. Carvalho, who saw 35 patients who all had the same sunburns and puncture wounds and the two women that died of a stroke.

19:37.000 --> 19:42.000
And he was just astonished that science can't even look at it.

19:42.000 --> 19:49.000
It's almost too much for humans to cope with, for our kind of epistemology to kind of understand.

19:49.000 --> 19:54.000
And so I think that's very fair to not come to a conclusion.

19:54.000 --> 19:58.000
But I hope that we can study this in a more official capacity.

19:58.000 --> 20:01.000
You obviously are running for president.

20:01.000 --> 20:05.000
There are rumors about conversations between you and Bolsonaro.

20:05.000 --> 20:09.000
I know you've had some issues with the Christian Democracy Party.

20:09.000 --> 20:17.000
If you were in office, would you start to have that conversation in a more official capacity?

20:17.000 --> 20:23.000
Would you try to get the best and brightest Brazilian scientists on these sorts of topics?

20:23.000 --> 20:30.000
Yes, provided that the common denominator is the national interest.

20:30.000 --> 20:35.000
The reserves have to protect national security.

20:35.000 --> 20:42.000
I believe that here we have a classic liberal common notion that the state should not have secrets.

20:42.000 --> 20:46.000
People can have their secrets. Companies can have their secrets.

20:46.000 --> 20:52.000
But there are some people who believe that the state should never hold secrets.

20:52.000 --> 21:07.000
I think there are secrets that are personal, secrets that relate to trade, corporative secrets, scientific secrets, technological secrets,

21:07.000 --> 21:11.000
and secrets that are national, of the public interest, that pertain to the state.

21:11.000 --> 21:18.000
The state, many times, is forced to adopt procedures that it can't announce publicly,

21:18.000 --> 21:25.000
especially in the areas of defense, foreign policy, and intelligence.

21:25.000 --> 21:35.000
This information will be revealed taking into account that there is a common agreement with other countries.

21:35.000 --> 21:45.000
That's why I conditioned the disclosure of this information from Brazil to the disclosure of the same information from the United States.

21:45.000 --> 21:50.000
Because a significant part of this information, and I guarantee you, is shared.

21:50.000 --> 21:57.000
If a man who is an expert migrated from the UK to the United States to do the same job,

21:57.000 --> 22:04.000
it's because there was some level of reciprocity, or you could even call it complicity,

22:04.000 --> 22:10.000
between the intelligence services of both countries, with regards to sharing this information.

22:10.000 --> 22:23.000
So, to the extent that this information may be shared and disclosed under a reciprocal agreement,

22:23.000 --> 22:29.000
this should be done for the benefit of science, for the dissemination of knowledge,

22:29.000 --> 22:38.000
even if it does eventually, in many cases, raise a sense of uncertainty and suspicion.

22:38.000 --> 22:44.000
Because, of course, if you admit that there is life outside of our planet, it's not a small matter.

22:44.000 --> 22:51.000
It isn't merely scientific, it involves morals, it involves philosophy, and religion.

22:51.000 --> 22:55.000
Some very sensitive nerves are going to be touched upon,

22:55.000 --> 23:00.000
that have to do with human history, human culture, and human traditions.

23:00.000 --> 23:07.000
So, it's very important to be cautious when you touch on these very delicate, sensitive issues,

23:07.000 --> 23:11.000
that have to do with the values of humanity, which is a must.

23:11.000 --> 23:17.000
Brazil is very interesting to touch on what you just said,

23:17.000 --> 23:22.000
because it sits at the intersection between traditional Catholicism,

23:22.000 --> 23:26.000
but you have people practicing traditional Catholicism,

23:26.000 --> 23:33.000
and also Candomblé, Umbanda, Alan Kardich is a, you know, spiritist from the 1850s,

23:33.000 --> 23:38.000
who obviously had his whole taxonomy of, you know, non-corporeal beings,

23:38.000 --> 23:41.000
you know, huge following in Brazil.

23:41.000 --> 23:46.000
And so, it's an interesting place in that you have the traditional religious element,

23:46.000 --> 23:50.000
but you also have the openness to some of these phenomena.

23:50.000 --> 23:56.000
And so, do you think, UFOs, in your mind, do you think it's consistent with Catholicism?

23:56.000 --> 23:59.000
How do you think people in Brazil would react?

23:59.000 --> 24:04.000
Because, in my experience, I almost think that it feels more natural,

24:04.000 --> 24:10.000
and it feels like they're more open to the phenomena than in places even like the U.S.

24:10.000 --> 24:18.000
Jesse, the concern regarding this subject appears in a very indirect way.

24:18.000 --> 24:22.000
When I was really young, there was a book that was released here.

24:22.000 --> 24:25.000
It was super successful. Everyone read it.

24:25.000 --> 24:31.000
Chariots of the Gods, the Portuguese title would translate to

24:31.000 --> 24:33.000
Were the Gods Astronauts?

24:33.000 --> 24:36.000
So, did they build the pyramids?

24:36.000 --> 24:39.000
And that ignited a wave of curiosity.

24:39.000 --> 24:43.000
Science fiction movies, movies about extraterrestrials,

24:43.000 --> 24:48.000
the possibility, or not, of the existence of extraterrestrial life.

24:48.000 --> 24:53.000
All of this raises a huge commotion, a lot of curiosity,

24:53.000 --> 24:57.000
especially when fiction addresses these ideas.

24:57.000 --> 25:01.000
So, it shows that people have a lot of interest and curiosity about the subject.

25:01.000 --> 25:05.000
And maybe even beyond interest and curiosity,

25:05.000 --> 25:11.000
it also reflects and reveals an existential concern.

25:11.000 --> 25:14.000
In other words, what are we in the world?

25:14.000 --> 25:16.000
Are we alone?

25:16.000 --> 25:19.000
What if we're not alone?

25:19.000 --> 25:24.000
How do you explain these other forms of life, these other beings?

25:24.000 --> 25:32.000
If we, here, were created in the image and likeness of God,

25:32.000 --> 25:35.000
if this was how man was created,

25:35.000 --> 25:41.000
are we ready for a different circumstance, another hypothesis?

25:41.000 --> 25:48.000
I believe that this has to be discussed with a lot of respect and a lot of caution.

25:48.000 --> 25:52.000
It's not something that can be subject of mere speculation.

25:52.000 --> 25:56.000
Unless we're talking about fiction, then it's absolutely fine.

25:56.000 --> 25:59.000
Movies, literature, talking about if Gods were astronauts,

25:59.000 --> 26:03.000
about an alien aboard a spaceship, that's fiction.

26:03.000 --> 26:09.000
Science, however, has another level of responsibility.

26:09.000 --> 26:11.000
It can't treat the subject that way.

26:11.000 --> 26:14.000
There's a book by Carl Sagan,

26:14.000 --> 26:18.000
who was probably one of the greatest scientific exponents in the United States,

26:18.000 --> 26:21.000
called Demon Haunted World,

26:21.000 --> 26:28.000
in which he touches upon the amount of scientific ignorance of American society,

26:28.000 --> 26:31.000
of rulers, of statesmen.

26:31.000 --> 26:37.000
Ronald Reagan, for example, would rely on a card reader to make his decisions.

26:37.000 --> 26:42.000
Back then he would say that there was only one that had a background in science,

26:42.000 --> 26:46.000
which was the Prime Minister of the UK, who had a degree in chemistry.

26:46.000 --> 26:50.000
So he would say that the average American was so ignorant, scientifically speaking,

26:50.000 --> 26:54.000
that they had the equivalent mentality of someone from the end of the 19th century.

26:54.000 --> 26:59.000
So these people would look at science from a great, great distance.

26:59.000 --> 27:03.000
Their worldview is explained by the presence of demons,

27:03.000 --> 27:06.000
and not by the presence of science.

27:06.000 --> 27:08.000
So that has to be taken into account.

27:08.000 --> 27:10.000
That situation.

27:10.000 --> 27:14.000
According to him, a survey was done with Americans,

27:14.000 --> 27:20.000
asking them how they believed the dinosaurs had vanished.

27:20.000 --> 27:22.000
And 90% of Americans would say,

27:22.000 --> 27:25.000
well, it's because they couldn't fit into Noah's Ark.

27:25.000 --> 27:27.000
And that's why they disappeared,

27:27.000 --> 27:31.000
because they were left out of Noah's Ark.

27:31.000 --> 27:34.000
So this issue has to be taken into account.

27:34.000 --> 27:37.000
And it's not exclusive to the US, it's all over the world.

27:37.000 --> 27:42.000
It's true.

27:42.000 --> 27:47.000
And that's a great book by Carl Sagan, The Demon Haunted World.

27:47.000 --> 27:51.000
Sagan's very interesting, though, because he also wrote the movie Contact,

27:51.000 --> 27:54.000
and the book, Pale Blue Dot.

27:54.000 --> 27:58.000
And in his early diaries as a child, he speculates a lot about UFOs.

27:58.000 --> 28:02.000
He has clearly a wonder for, you know, the universe.

28:02.000 --> 28:06.000
And he talks about, you know, platonic objects, you know,

28:06.000 --> 28:11.000
things like higher dimensional space objects that, you know,

28:11.000 --> 28:14.000
like a tesseract that you would only see the shadow of

28:14.000 --> 28:16.000
if you were kind of on a lower plane.

28:16.000 --> 28:19.000
And so, you know, I go back and forth.

28:19.000 --> 28:22.000
I wonder what he actually believed about UFOs.

28:22.000 --> 28:25.000
And I know Nancy Reagan and probably Ronald Reagan

28:25.000 --> 28:26.000
had their astrologer.

28:26.000 --> 28:32.000
But maybe sometimes, you know, mystical ways of knowing

28:32.000 --> 28:35.000
are also, you know, valid, too.

28:35.000 --> 28:40.000
You know, Baba Vanga would, you know, regularly advise world leaders.

28:40.000 --> 28:43.000
I believe Bolsonaro, who you've, you know,

28:43.000 --> 28:45.000
now have sort of a friendly relationship with,

28:45.000 --> 28:48.000
he, I think, has an astrologer as well.

28:48.000 --> 28:51.000
Yes, and there is a type of astrology,

28:51.000 --> 28:55.000
which would turn to knowledge as well,

28:55.000 --> 28:58.000
which is Egyptian astrology.

28:58.000 --> 29:03.000
It's not the astrology that comes from horoscopes that you read in the newspaper.

29:03.000 --> 29:05.000
That's another thing.

29:05.000 --> 29:10.000
The astrology that was referred to in Egypt

29:10.000 --> 29:16.000
was based on the rigorous examination of the stars.

29:16.000 --> 29:25.000
It wasn't this mere poppycock made to sell these packages with astrology and horoscope issues

29:25.000 --> 29:27.000
that were sold with daily papers.

29:27.000 --> 29:33.000
There's another important book by Carl Sagan, which it's called, I'm not sure in English,

29:33.000 --> 29:36.000
but in Brazil it's called Billions and Billions.

29:36.000 --> 29:42.000
And he touches upon this issue with a lot of care and a lot of sensibility.

29:42.000 --> 29:45.000
And I believe that in this way,

29:45.000 --> 29:54.000
I believe that the care taken into how science should approach this subject

29:54.000 --> 29:59.000
has to do with taking into account the scientific knowledge of people.

29:59.000 --> 30:03.000
Because you shouldn't really breed desperation or create panic.

30:03.000 --> 30:05.000
It's very easy to create panic.

30:05.000 --> 30:14.000
You know the Orson Welles story, the radio show.

30:14.000 --> 30:20.000
In other words, he created panic by simply telling a story that wasn't real.

30:20.000 --> 30:22.000
It was fake news.

30:22.000 --> 30:27.000
But since he was such a competent and efficient communicator,

30:27.000 --> 30:31.000
as Orson Welles was known for, he whipped up a panic on a news radio show.

30:31.000 --> 30:35.000
So I understand the caution and the prudence of science,

30:35.000 --> 30:40.000
because it's different from a mere opinion,

30:40.000 --> 30:47.000
from a piece of literature, a short story, a novel, a movie.

30:47.000 --> 30:51.000
When science makes a statement about a specific subject,

30:51.000 --> 30:54.000
there's a weight to it,

30:54.000 --> 30:59.000
which is not the same as what fiction authors write about.

31:02.000 --> 31:03.000
Very well said.

31:03.000 --> 31:06.000
I want to go kind of in chronological order.

31:06.000 --> 31:11.000
So we talked about Operation Prado, Kolaris in 1977.

31:11.000 --> 31:20.000
In 1986, in May, you had 21 unidentified objects spotted in four different Brazilian states.

31:20.000 --> 31:26.000
You had six fighter jets that were dispatched from bases near Brasilia and Rio.

31:26.000 --> 31:29.000
And all of them were scrambled by these objects.

31:29.000 --> 31:34.000
And you have the Air Force making a very fascinating official statement on the whole thing,

31:34.000 --> 31:40.000
saying these were basically aircraft flying in ways that we technically don't understand.

31:40.000 --> 31:44.000
They were flying, you know, at extreme speeds and maneuverability.

31:44.000 --> 31:47.000
What do you know about that night in 1986?

31:47.000 --> 31:54.000
Yes, and in fact, the fighters that we had at the time were state of the art.

31:54.000 --> 32:02.000
The F-5 jets, which were American, but also the Mirage fighters that came from a base close to Brasilia,

32:02.000 --> 32:09.000
the Annapolis Air Base, which was built very close to the capital of the country.

32:09.000 --> 32:14.000
And those jets flew from the base in Santa Cruz, in the state of Rio de Janeiro,

32:14.000 --> 32:20.000
and from the Annapolis Air Base in Goiás in the attempt to intercept the UFOs.

32:20.000 --> 32:29.000
But after that, other pilots in the Air Force reported very similar phenomena.

32:29.000 --> 32:39.000
And long after that, and in the 80s, there were many reports by pilots from the Air Force that were documented.

32:39.000 --> 32:45.000
One of them, for example, was a pilot that was flying from Chile to Brazil, flying a fighter jet.

32:45.000 --> 32:52.000
And he says that an object made its approach at a very high speed,

32:52.000 --> 32:57.000
and that when he tried to approach it, the object took off, and this is documented,

32:57.000 --> 33:04.000
at a speed of 25,000 kilometers an hour, according to what the radar picked up.

33:04.000 --> 33:11.000
So the existence of the phenomena is undisputed.

33:11.000 --> 33:18.000
I sat down with José Manuel Fernández, who worked for the Brazilian Air Force for 34 years,

33:18.000 --> 33:25.000
and was an air traffic controller at Sao Paulo's Congonhas Airport on May 19, 1986.

33:25.000 --> 33:34.000
This was the same night as the mass sighting known as Brazil's Night of UFOs.

33:34.000 --> 33:40.000
Fernández watched in real time as fighter jets scrambled to intercept these UFOs,

33:40.000 --> 33:44.000
only to be completely outmaneuvered and outmatched.

33:44.000 --> 33:47.000
So I relayed the information.

33:47.000 --> 33:54.000
I could see the fighter jet, the F-5 fighter jet.

33:54.000 --> 34:01.000
You know, reach supersonic speed to try and reach the object.

34:01.000 --> 34:10.000
But curiously enough, and I can assure you, that I speak the truth.

34:10.000 --> 34:16.000
Even though the F-5 was moving at supersonic speed,

34:16.000 --> 34:21.000
as the fighter jet was in pursuit of the object,

34:21.000 --> 34:26.000
I could even see the tracks that were left by the fighter jet.

34:26.000 --> 34:31.000
You know, the object was just playing hide and seek.

34:31.000 --> 34:35.000
It would just show up and appear at a very distant point.

34:35.000 --> 34:38.000
So when the F-5 would try to come closer,

34:38.000 --> 34:41.000
the object would just simply disappear,

34:41.000 --> 34:45.000
and then just reappear further down.

34:56.000 --> 35:03.000
What's up for debate is what these phenomena are.

35:03.000 --> 35:09.000
That's what still has to be investigated, discussed, identified.

35:09.000 --> 35:17.000
And this could also be an effort that is more in the interest of science

35:17.000 --> 35:19.000
than the interest of defense.

35:19.000 --> 35:25.000
Because really, when it comes to the national defense of countries,

35:25.000 --> 35:29.000
this was never reported as a risk or threat, right?

35:29.000 --> 35:31.000
Or registered as such.

35:31.000 --> 35:36.000
The information that these objects would be trying to collect or capture

35:36.000 --> 35:41.000
really cannot be verified.

35:41.000 --> 35:48.000
However, in terms of threats or risks or even damage for the defense of Brazil,

35:48.000 --> 35:51.000
the United States, England, Russia,

35:51.000 --> 35:56.000
there's no record that any of these phenomena resulted in damage for these countries.

35:56.000 --> 35:59.000
So therefore, from the point of view of national defense,

35:59.000 --> 36:03.000
it's a permanent reason of concern, but it's not really a risk.

36:03.000 --> 36:08.000
So much so that the concerns in Brazil in the area of defense have subsided.

36:08.000 --> 36:14.000
But what still remains is the question, the shadowy area,

36:14.000 --> 36:18.000
what hasn't been brought to light in terms of science.

36:18.000 --> 36:20.000
To this day, from a scientific point of view,

36:20.000 --> 36:25.000
there's more dark than light when it comes to these phenomena.

36:25.000 --> 36:33.000
You've mentioned some of these UFO cases in the context of advanced technology.

36:33.000 --> 36:40.000
Do you think that some of what we've experienced maybe on this night, for example, in 1986,

36:40.000 --> 36:47.000
or some of these other Brazilian encounters are not in fact, you know, other beings,

36:47.000 --> 36:49.000
but they're our own advanced technology.

36:49.000 --> 36:53.000
Obviously, the United States has conducted military, you know,

36:53.000 --> 36:56.000
secret operations in Brazil since World War II.

36:56.000 --> 37:07.000
Jesse, it's very hard to believe that the United States commands the technology to produce objects

37:07.000 --> 37:11.000
that can move at 25,000 kilometers an hour.

37:11.000 --> 37:22.000
The U.S. sacrificed a generation of their best pilots in trying to overtake the Russians during the space race.

37:22.000 --> 37:31.000
When Gagarin, Yuri Gagarin, took his first orbit trip and the world was astonished,

37:31.000 --> 37:35.000
the U.S. entered a situation of despair and panic

37:35.000 --> 37:41.000
because they were surpassed in an event that gave the Soviet Union international projection.

37:41.000 --> 37:49.000
Gagarin was received in New York and São Paulo as a celebrity, respected, cherished and admired around the world.

37:49.000 --> 37:54.000
To overcome this, an American author wrote a novel about this.

37:54.000 --> 37:56.000
They actually made a movie about it as well.

37:56.000 --> 38:01.000
They brought together the best pilots in America to an air base.

38:01.000 --> 38:06.000
And the majority of them died trying to do it because they didn't have the equipment.

38:06.000 --> 38:08.000
They didn't have the material.

38:08.000 --> 38:12.000
It couldn't resist a space flight.

38:12.000 --> 38:21.000
And the widows learned of the deaths of their husbands, of these very young pilots because they didn't have the right material.

38:21.000 --> 38:31.000
If the U.S. in fact had the material that would resist what was seen involving these objects,

38:31.000 --> 38:35.000
they wouldn't have sacrificed their own pilots.

38:35.000 --> 38:41.000
I'm not sure if it was Paul Kennedy, a writer, who described this in a very nice novel about…

38:41.000 --> 38:44.000
No, it was the same one who wrote A Bonfire of the Vanities.

38:44.000 --> 38:46.000
This one that wrote a book.

38:46.000 --> 38:49.000
Tom Wolfe wrote the right stuff.

38:49.000 --> 39:01.000
Tom Wolfe wrote the novel about the sacrifice of these young pilots for America in the space race.

39:01.000 --> 39:08.000
So I don't think that it had anything to do with espionage on part of the U.S. or even the Russians.

39:08.000 --> 39:17.000
They didn't have that material available with that degree of resistance that would endure that kind of speed.

39:17.000 --> 39:20.000
It would have melted by much slower speed than that.

39:20.000 --> 39:27.000
So that kind of explanation just isn't reasonable.

39:27.000 --> 39:29.000
Yeah.

39:29.000 --> 39:34.000
I mean, even in the 80s, the U.S. was just starting to build stealth craft.

39:34.000 --> 39:44.000
But the rumor, even the rumors of the most advanced stealth craft was Mach 4, Mach 5, which is, you know, 3,000 to 4,000 miles per hour.

39:44.000 --> 39:50.000
So 25,000 is just orders of magnitude more advanced than, you know, anything that we had.

39:50.000 --> 39:53.000
Maybe you had some unmanned drone there, but I don't know.

39:53.000 --> 39:55.000
I think it's very hard to believe.

39:55.000 --> 40:07.000
So you would agree with the Air Force Minister Brigadier Octavio Julio Morea Lima's statement that these things, we detected them, they were what they were, and that the facts are what they are.

40:07.000 --> 40:09.000
And we don't know what they are.

40:09.000 --> 40:11.000
You would agree with that, that these are sort of genuine?

40:11.000 --> 40:12.000
I agree.

40:12.000 --> 40:13.000
Absolutely.

40:13.000 --> 40:14.000
Totally.

40:14.000 --> 40:15.000
We…

40:15.000 --> 40:19.000
We don't know what they are, what these phenomena are.

40:19.000 --> 40:21.000
We don't know what these objects are.

40:21.000 --> 40:27.000
And it's so hard to identify them that science itself is unable to develop a theory on it.

40:27.000 --> 40:31.000
They can develop a theory about what they are not.

40:31.000 --> 40:33.000
They are not man-made.

40:33.000 --> 40:35.000
They cannot be man-made.

40:35.000 --> 40:51.000
Because in science, the ability to build that kind of material at that level of resistance, there's no alloy that can resist that kind of procedure of these objects and these phenomena.

40:51.000 --> 40:55.000
No man-made object would be able to move at that speed.

40:55.000 --> 41:06.000
I mean, look, in the 40s, in the UK, and then in the 70s, in the 80s, what kind of material would resist 25,000 km an hour? Impossible.

41:06.000 --> 41:09.000
Not here, not in the US, not in Russia.

41:09.000 --> 41:11.000
Okay, but who else could have done it?

41:11.000 --> 41:22.000
Who was leading the special alloy production for rockets and spaceships were the US and Russia.

41:22.000 --> 41:24.000
That's it.

41:24.000 --> 41:28.000
But not at that level of sophistication, no.

41:28.000 --> 41:31.000
Some of the patterns are just remarkable.

41:31.000 --> 41:37.000
You see 90 degree turns, so it's breaking Newton's laws, conservation of momentum.

41:37.000 --> 41:47.000
And Captain Viriato recorded this thing on radar, and he recorded it Mach 15, doing a zigzag pattern.

41:47.000 --> 42:03.000
If you were elected president or vice president, would you ever sort of look into this radar data and consider exposing some of this radar data and maybe the Super 8 footage from Kolaris to the public for broader research and study?

42:03.000 --> 42:18.000
I would rather look into all those reports, to look at all the footage and talk and consult with those who are interested in the subject matter at hand.

42:18.000 --> 42:23.000
There is multilateral interest, we're not the only ones interested in it.

42:23.000 --> 42:35.000
There's probably this interest in identifying that phenomenon in the States, same in Russia, maybe in China as well, Germany or the UK.

42:35.000 --> 42:57.000
So I believe that this should be the object of a multilateral agreement among countries, with the inclusion of the two most important key elements, which are the fields of defense and of science, the world of science.

42:57.000 --> 43:04.000
Perhaps an international conference to be responsible for that.

43:04.000 --> 43:24.000
A consultation with experts and scientists, physicists and experts in defense, so that the world can start looking into this with more transparency, more responsibility and more scientific curiosity.

43:24.000 --> 43:41.000
So that these phenomena are not just constrained to the world of fiction, because fiction can explore very successfully the curiosity and humankind's existential concern as well.

43:41.000 --> 43:49.000
That's a beautiful vision and I hope that happens, because there are all these patterns that start to develop if you deeply research this stuff.

43:49.000 --> 43:54.000
But I think a lot of the scientific community just looks away, they don't look at the patterns.

43:54.000 --> 44:04.000
And so, I don't know, one example is that, you know, the Amazon River Basin is 7,000 or I think it's 7 million square kilometers.

44:04.000 --> 44:12.000
And you have obviously outlets, rivers all over Brazil, and water is a very important part of the UFO phenomena.

44:12.000 --> 44:17.000
They often seem to go submerge into water, come out of water.

44:17.000 --> 44:24.000
They're indigenous myths going back, you know, centuries about, you know, water people and that sort of thing.

44:24.000 --> 44:35.000
So, it would be very interesting to develop an international coalition and have our best and brightest scientists from all different countries really in an unbiased way investigating this.

44:35.000 --> 44:48.000
Well, that's probably because when it comes to unknown phenomena in space, there really is no visible financial interest.

44:48.000 --> 45:00.000
Einstein got to the theory of relativity because there was a search by mankind to turn matter into energy.

45:00.000 --> 45:13.000
So, you had capitalism and expansion, the system needed energy, which was scarce, but it was the main input for the development of capitalism.

45:13.000 --> 45:19.000
And scientists from all over the world were looking for a way to turn matter into energy.

45:19.000 --> 45:31.000
And the theory of relativity, Einstein's equation, which is comprised of energy equals mass times the speed of light squared,

45:31.000 --> 45:38.000
is basically to turn a small particle of matter into a large amount of energy.

45:38.000 --> 45:41.000
That is what led to the theory of relativity.

45:41.000 --> 45:48.000
It has nothing to do with the need of understanding and identifying these phenomena.

45:48.000 --> 45:52.000
There is no clear financial interest in that.

45:52.000 --> 46:02.000
If there were, perhaps the world would have mobilized academia, scientists.

46:02.000 --> 46:10.000
The United States spends over half of their budgets on military research.

46:10.000 --> 46:15.000
But this was never the focus of this investigation.

46:15.000 --> 46:26.000
So, I think that once that comes up as a possibility, maybe then science will actually be interested.

46:26.000 --> 46:31.000
Because now it's more of an existential issue, a curiosity.

46:31.000 --> 46:36.000
And unfortunately, science is funded, but it's not funded by curiosity.

46:36.000 --> 46:46.000
It's got much more practical objectives and much more material drivers than scientific curiosity.

46:46.000 --> 47:01.000
However, governments can mobilize part of their science towards multilateral initiatives to first gather information.

47:01.000 --> 47:08.000
And once information has been compiled, to work out what's common and how to move forward.

47:08.000 --> 47:13.000
Perhaps nothing can be solved in a first conference on that topic.

47:13.000 --> 47:27.000
But you could establish a process to shine a light on a matter that, to this day, there's only been shadows.

47:27.000 --> 47:29.000
Yeah, well said.

47:29.000 --> 47:39.000
And I think as much as studying UFOs or exotic propulsion or some of these, you know, free energy, it seems sort of useless.

47:39.000 --> 47:49.000
I think in many ways, you know, even if you look at semiconductors, it came from a bunch of people who were considered crazy in Copenhagen thinking about the nature of reality.

47:49.000 --> 47:54.000
And before that, they said electromagnetism was the last act.

47:54.000 --> 47:56.000
There'd be nothing, you know, after that.

47:56.000 --> 47:58.000
And then you get the quantum revolution.

47:58.000 --> 48:11.000
And even with electromagnetism, Marconi, you know, was told that he was, you know, not a very good student and that he was crazy, that, you know, you'd never be able to send electromagnetic waves as far as he did.

48:11.000 --> 48:21.000
And so I think there's a lot of value actually in government spending on science that seems useless because that ends up being the most useful.

48:21.000 --> 48:27.000
It's the science that is the most existential, deals with the contemplation of reality itself.

48:27.000 --> 48:37.000
Exactly, because science comes from experimentation.

48:37.000 --> 48:41.000
The steam engine has been around for 2,000 years.

48:41.000 --> 48:50.000
Someone from Egypt, from Alexandria, realized that when he heated up water, steam created mechanical energy.

48:50.000 --> 48:55.000
But that remained as it was for 2,000 years until someone in the UK said,

48:55.000 --> 49:02.000
actually that mechanical force discovered by Heron from Alexandria could actually move a steam loom.

49:02.000 --> 49:11.000
And then Heron from Alexandria's steam engine became what drove the industrial revolution in England.

49:11.000 --> 49:15.000
And then the military revolution.

49:15.000 --> 49:22.000
Because then the UK created the steam engine and the British Navy ruled over China and then over the world.

49:22.000 --> 49:36.000
So this transition from experimental research and knowledge to technological knowledge and economic activity is a natural step.

49:36.000 --> 49:38.000
And humankind is familiar with it.

49:38.000 --> 49:48.000
Most probably Einstein wasn't thinking about the atom bomb when he thought about turning matter into energy.

49:48.000 --> 49:56.000
But what happened was, just like the steam engine was turned into the steam gunboat,

49:56.000 --> 50:06.000
you see, matter, uranium, was transformed into the atom bomb, which was dropped on Hiroshima and Nagasaki.

50:06.000 --> 50:10.000
But that's how science works, for better or worse.

50:10.000 --> 50:12.000
Hmm.

50:12.000 --> 50:13.000
Hmm.

50:13.000 --> 50:14.000
Hmm.

50:14.000 --> 50:16.000
There's a small town in southern Brazil called Varginia.

50:16.000 --> 50:19.000
It has 130,000 people.

50:19.000 --> 50:25.000
And in January of 1996, something absolutely remarkable happens there.

50:25.000 --> 50:27.000
My friend is a documentarian.

50:27.000 --> 50:28.000
His name is James Fox.

50:28.000 --> 50:31.000
And he made a movie called Moment of Contact.

50:31.000 --> 50:34.800
and he's spoken to maybe 15 to 20 people

50:34.800 --> 50:37.200
between people who have seen beings

50:37.200 --> 50:39.220
and people who have seen the craft.

50:39.620 --> 50:41.680
He's triangulated the flight path

50:41.680 --> 50:45.780
and basically this cigar-shaped Tic Tac craft

50:45.780 --> 50:48.700
seemed to have some sort of puncture in it.

50:49.080 --> 50:50.320
Gas was coming out of the back.

50:50.740 --> 50:52.960
It crashed on something called the Maolini Farm.

50:53.120 --> 50:55.380
An ultralight pilot named Carlos DeSouza,

50:55.380 --> 50:56.800
who was also a geography teacher,

50:57.660 --> 51:00.200
held pieces of the craft in his hands

51:00.200 --> 51:15.000
It seemed to have bounced

51:15.000 --> 51:16.860
the rear end of the craft,

51:17.420 --> 51:18.780
which was completely destroyed.

51:19.700 --> 51:20.940
There were pieces everywhere

51:20.940 --> 51:22.620
and the front of it,

51:22.620 --> 51:24.380
which was practically half of it,

51:24.860 --> 51:27.900
slid further and ran into a tree.

51:28.760 --> 51:30.240
That's literally what it did.

51:30.560 --> 51:32.080
It ran into a tree,

51:33.300 --> 51:34.740
hit the tree and stopped.

51:35.220 --> 51:36.840
Thinking he's looking at a blimp

51:36.840 --> 51:39.360
or some kind of experimental aircraft,

51:39.900 --> 51:42.800
Carlos' first thought is that there were people inside.

51:43.300 --> 51:45.460
So he rushed to the crash site to help.

51:45.740 --> 51:49.000
And that's where he realized this wasn't a normal crash.

51:49.000 --> 51:52.000
The very first thing that I observed

51:52.000 --> 51:53.740
and that really caught my attention

51:53.740 --> 51:54.660
was the smell.

51:55.620 --> 51:57.340
Because at that moment,

51:57.560 --> 52:01.020
what I was expecting was the smell of diesel fuel

52:01.020 --> 52:04.100
or kerosene or aircraft fuel.

52:05.120 --> 52:06.780
It's normally a very strong smell.

52:07.500 --> 52:08.500
And on the contrary,

52:09.060 --> 52:11.320
the smell that I felt at the crash site

52:11.320 --> 52:12.620
felt like ammonia.

52:13.620 --> 52:14.800
It was very strong.

52:14.800 --> 52:16.620
I don't know what was the fuel

52:16.620 --> 52:18.040
or the substance that was there,

52:18.200 --> 52:20.420
but it was a very strong smell,

52:20.540 --> 52:21.400
something different.

52:21.820 --> 52:23.780
And it began to burn my eyes.

52:25.240 --> 52:27.860
A military convoy then pulled up

52:27.860 --> 52:30.600
and soldiers started to secure the area.

52:30.980 --> 52:32.060
Before they reached him,

52:32.220 --> 52:34.220
something on the ground caught his eye,

52:34.600 --> 52:36.900
shiny pieces of metal from the wreckage.

52:37.140 --> 52:38.120
He picked it up.

52:38.500 --> 52:39.920
When he tried to crumple it,

52:40.100 --> 52:42.580
the material went back to its original shape.

52:42.580 --> 52:45.440
And a soldier,

52:46.160 --> 52:46.780
huge,

52:47.340 --> 52:48.140
really strong,

52:48.320 --> 52:49.600
probably two meters tall,

52:49.820 --> 52:51.040
really strong,

52:51.100 --> 52:52.940
came running, shouting,

52:53.260 --> 52:54.020
get out of here,

52:54.160 --> 52:54.860
get out of here.

52:55.240 --> 52:56.720
And just at that time,

52:57.040 --> 52:59.320
I could see quite a few pieces of debris

52:59.320 --> 53:00.400
on the ground,

53:00.480 --> 53:01.300
and I picked them up.

53:01.400 --> 53:02.900
And it was kind of curved.

53:03.220 --> 53:04.520
And then I was surprised

53:04.520 --> 53:06.040
to see how light it was.

53:06.040 --> 53:08.560
You know,

53:08.900 --> 53:09.820
aluminum foil

53:09.820 --> 53:11.060
that you use

53:11.060 --> 53:12.620
to wrap up chicken

53:12.620 --> 53:13.760
to roast

53:13.760 --> 53:15.500
that you use normally in the kitchen?

53:15.920 --> 53:17.340
It was that kind of weight.

53:17.720 --> 53:19.180
It didn't weigh anything at all.

53:22.020 --> 53:22.980
And I thought,

53:23.140 --> 53:23.480
well,

53:23.580 --> 53:24.600
this is strange.

53:26.660 --> 53:27.280
All right.

53:27.520 --> 53:28.360
So I said,

53:28.440 --> 53:29.360
I'll keep it.

53:29.600 --> 53:30.560
And so I crunched it up.

53:30.560 --> 53:32.880
And so I made this kind of movement,

53:33.080 --> 53:33.340
you know,

53:33.400 --> 53:34.340
to put it in my pocket.

53:36.320 --> 53:37.000
And what happened

53:37.000 --> 53:38.740
was this foil or this sheet

53:38.740 --> 53:40.040
regained its shape.

53:41.320 --> 53:44.060
Sounds a lot like the Roswell crash material.

53:44.520 --> 53:45.240
Foil-like,

53:45.560 --> 53:46.080
weightless,

53:46.300 --> 53:47.700
and impossible to deform.

53:48.160 --> 53:49.620
Carlos wanted to keep it,

53:49.920 --> 53:50.980
but things took a turn

53:50.980 --> 53:52.420
when he was ordered to leave

53:52.420 --> 53:53.220
at gunpoint.

53:53.220 --> 53:54.800
And then

53:54.800 --> 53:55.960
that soldier

53:55.960 --> 53:57.120
arrived,

53:57.560 --> 53:58.520
took his rifle

53:58.520 --> 53:59.600
and started hitting me

53:59.600 --> 54:00.100
on the chest

54:00.100 --> 54:00.540
and saying,

54:00.620 --> 54:01.260
get out of here.

54:01.480 --> 54:02.660
And I started to question him,

54:02.720 --> 54:03.200
saying, no.

54:04.660 --> 54:05.940
There are people there

54:05.940 --> 54:07.480
who are going to need help.

54:07.620 --> 54:08.400
I'm going to help them.

54:08.500 --> 54:09.380
I'm a pilot, man.

54:09.480 --> 54:10.640
I know what they're going through.

54:11.300 --> 54:12.560
He took a step back,

54:13.680 --> 54:14.500
raised his gun,

54:15.000 --> 54:15.540
cocked it,

54:15.900 --> 54:17.040
and pointed it

54:17.040 --> 54:17.740
at my head.

54:19.360 --> 54:20.360
Pointing at my head

54:20.360 --> 54:21.360
right here

54:21.360 --> 54:22.740
and said to me,

54:23.220 --> 54:25.160
I'm not asking.

54:25.680 --> 54:26.580
I'm giving you an order.

54:26.780 --> 54:27.700
If you don't leave,

54:28.020 --> 54:29.680
I'm going to blow your brains out.

54:31.400 --> 54:31.960
And

54:31.960 --> 54:33.460
he was later

54:33.460 --> 54:34.640
apprehended

54:34.640 --> 54:35.340
by some men

54:35.340 --> 54:36.200
in dark suits.

54:36.780 --> 54:38.160
The beings then ran off.

54:38.760 --> 54:39.420
Three women

54:39.420 --> 54:40.020
who seemed

54:40.020 --> 54:41.100
very honest

54:41.100 --> 54:41.700
to me

54:41.700 --> 54:42.900
saw the beings.

54:43.020 --> 54:43.720
It was a red,

54:43.920 --> 54:44.560
you know,

54:44.640 --> 54:45.420
red eyes,

54:45.920 --> 54:46.480
brown

54:46.480 --> 54:48.260
with skin color.

54:49.020 --> 54:49.300
And

54:49.300 --> 54:50.940
it seems like

54:50.940 --> 54:51.500
one of the beings

54:51.500 --> 54:52.500
was also apprehended

54:52.500 --> 54:53.200
by the military.

54:53.220 --> 54:54.300
by

54:54.300 --> 54:55.480
a guy named

54:55.480 --> 54:55.880
Marcos

54:55.880 --> 54:56.760
Cheresi

54:56.760 --> 54:58.180
who was a soldier

54:58.180 --> 54:58.960
and

54:58.960 --> 55:00.480
that he died

55:00.480 --> 55:01.720
due to a puncture wound

55:01.720 --> 55:02.460
from the being.

55:03.180 --> 55:03.500
And

55:03.500 --> 55:04.200
even

55:04.200 --> 55:04.940
Armando

55:04.940 --> 55:05.640
Fortunato

55:05.640 --> 55:06.920
who did the autopsy

55:06.920 --> 55:08.520
basically

55:08.520 --> 55:09.780
saw it was a

55:09.780 --> 55:10.220
bacterial

55:10.220 --> 55:10.920
that he had never

55:10.920 --> 55:11.760
seen before.

55:11.760 --> 55:12.920
and

55:12.920 --> 55:13.580
then all of these

55:13.580 --> 55:14.620
people at the hospital

55:14.620 --> 55:16.020
mentioned treating

55:16.020 --> 55:17.240
an ET being.

55:17.620 --> 55:19.060
There's a neurosurgeon

55:19.060 --> 55:20.160
Italo Venturelli

55:20.160 --> 55:21.380
who manages

55:21.380 --> 55:22.820
the whole chain

55:22.820 --> 55:23.680
of three hospitals

55:23.680 --> 55:23.920
but

55:23.920 --> 55:25.020
regionalis

55:25.020 --> 55:25.640
where they held

55:25.640 --> 55:26.180
this being.

55:26.420 --> 55:27.420
He was there

55:27.420 --> 55:28.140
and he was checking

55:28.140 --> 55:29.260
the work of a guy

55:29.260 --> 55:30.460
who stitched up

55:30.460 --> 55:31.520
and actually worked on

55:31.520 --> 55:31.980
did some

55:31.980 --> 55:32.960
basic,

55:32.960 --> 55:33.600
you know,

55:33.660 --> 55:34.640
operating procedure

55:34.640 --> 55:36.200
on this being.

55:36.540 --> 55:37.440
So you get

55:37.440 --> 55:38.700
thing after thing

55:38.700 --> 55:39.200
after thing

55:39.200 --> 55:40.080
this whole chain

55:40.080 --> 55:40.740
of custody

55:40.740 --> 55:41.620
of this being

55:41.620 --> 55:42.420
different witnesses.

55:42.900 --> 55:43.460
To me,

55:43.500 --> 55:44.220
it's the most

55:44.220 --> 55:45.580
interesting UFO case

55:45.580 --> 55:46.220
globally

55:46.220 --> 55:47.980
as far as

55:47.980 --> 55:48.780
documentation

55:48.780 --> 55:50.460
because it's from

55:50.460 --> 55:50.980
the 90s

55:50.980 --> 55:51.360
and a lot of

55:51.360 --> 55:51.720
these people

55:51.720 --> 55:52.600
are still alive.

55:52.600 --> 55:53.960
What do you think

55:53.960 --> 55:54.880
about this case?

55:56.260 --> 55:57.240
You know that

55:57.240 --> 55:58.280
that event

55:58.280 --> 55:59.300
created a celebrity

55:59.300 --> 55:59.920
in Brazil.

56:00.540 --> 56:01.380
Its name is

56:01.380 --> 56:03.020
the Varginha ET.

56:05.300 --> 56:06.420
Nobody saw

56:06.420 --> 56:07.360
the Varginha ET

56:07.360 --> 56:08.460
but everyone

56:08.460 --> 56:09.600
knows about

56:09.600 --> 56:10.000
the ET.

56:11.060 --> 56:11.720
By the way,

56:12.500 --> 56:13.640
this phenomenon

56:13.640 --> 56:15.140
the Varginha ET

56:15.140 --> 56:16.240
became a

56:16.240 --> 56:17.040
national phenomenon.

56:18.120 --> 56:18.560
In fact,

56:18.700 --> 56:19.220
sometimes

56:19.220 --> 56:20.060
people will

56:20.060 --> 56:20.680
kind of

56:20.680 --> 56:22.260
poke fun at it

56:22.260 --> 56:24.700
they'll joke

56:24.700 --> 56:25.340
around about

56:25.340 --> 56:26.580
when someone

56:26.580 --> 56:27.800
becomes a celebrity

56:27.800 --> 56:28.580
or famous

56:28.580 --> 56:29.240
they say

56:29.240 --> 56:29.520
that they're

56:29.520 --> 56:30.340
more famous

56:30.340 --> 56:31.580
than the Varginha ET.

56:32.220 --> 56:32.520
Now,

56:33.280 --> 56:34.220
even if the ET

56:34.220 --> 56:34.840
itself

56:34.840 --> 56:35.840
remains,

56:36.440 --> 56:37.140
shall we say,

56:37.620 --> 56:38.320
unseen,

56:39.420 --> 56:40.200
the phenomenon

56:40.200 --> 56:41.440
was documented

56:41.440 --> 56:43.220
and also

56:43.220 --> 56:44.140
documented

56:44.140 --> 56:45.940
both

56:45.940 --> 56:47.320
by the military

56:47.320 --> 56:48.540
and in the

56:48.540 --> 56:49.840
field of health,

56:50.220 --> 56:51.060
the medical field,

56:51.060 --> 56:52.500
the testimonials,

56:53.080 --> 56:53.960
if not all of them,

56:54.240 --> 56:54.960
but most of them,

56:55.620 --> 56:57.260
are publicly

56:57.260 --> 56:58.300
well-known,

56:58.760 --> 56:59.320
disclosed.

56:59.880 --> 57:00.600
We're talking

57:00.600 --> 57:01.380
about testimony

57:01.380 --> 57:02.160
from doctors

57:02.160 --> 57:02.960
like Dr.

57:03.040 --> 57:04.160
Italo Venturelli,

57:04.620 --> 57:06.020
a chief neurosurgeon

57:06.020 --> 57:06.880
from Hospital

57:06.880 --> 57:07.360
Regional.

57:07.980 --> 57:09.000
By his own account,

57:09.140 --> 57:10.120
he showed up to work

57:10.120 --> 57:10.580
like it was

57:10.580 --> 57:11.440
any other day.

57:12.600 --> 57:13.740
His colleague,

57:13.920 --> 57:15.060
another neurosurgeon

57:15.060 --> 57:15.880
named Dr.

57:15.980 --> 57:16.900
Marcos Venesis,

57:17.420 --> 57:18.480
pulled him aside.

57:18.480 --> 57:19.380
At first,

57:19.520 --> 57:20.540
he showed Venturelli

57:20.540 --> 57:21.160
a tape,

57:21.520 --> 57:22.340
grainy footage

57:22.340 --> 57:23.380
of what looked like

57:23.380 --> 57:24.300
a small child

57:24.300 --> 57:25.260
with a deformity

57:25.260 --> 57:26.380
getting patched up

57:26.380 --> 57:27.440
after a procedure.

57:27.820 --> 57:28.300
But then,

57:28.420 --> 57:29.260
Marcos Venesis

57:29.260 --> 57:30.800
insisted that Italo

57:30.800 --> 57:31.880
see his patient

57:31.880 --> 57:32.580
in person.

57:33.540 --> 57:34.980
He brings Italo

57:34.980 --> 57:35.800
into the room,

57:36.180 --> 57:36.840
where he came

57:36.840 --> 57:37.820
face-to-face

57:37.820 --> 57:38.560
with the being

57:38.560 --> 57:40.940
for four entire minutes.

57:40.940 --> 57:42.580
He was just lying there

57:42.580 --> 57:43.720
with a surgical drape.

57:44.900 --> 57:45.700
One hand in

57:45.700 --> 57:46.400
and the other out

57:46.400 --> 57:46.920
like this.

57:47.420 --> 57:47.920
Nothing here

57:47.920 --> 57:48.620
and it's peaceful.

57:49.960 --> 57:51.500
The bed positioned upright

57:51.500 --> 57:53.460
like we do

57:53.460 --> 57:54.760
for neurological patients.

57:55.560 --> 57:55.980
Eventually,

57:56.160 --> 57:57.320
the reality sunk in

57:57.320 --> 57:58.340
that this patient

57:58.340 --> 57:59.600
wasn't human.

58:00.760 --> 58:01.820
He had arms.

58:02.360 --> 58:03.120
He had a chest.

58:03.860 --> 58:04.600
Hal's wife

58:04.600 --> 58:05.900
asked if he had nipples.

58:06.260 --> 58:07.040
I didn't see nipples.

58:08.040 --> 58:09.140
I didn't see a nipple

58:09.140 --> 58:10.660
lying there like that.

58:11.320 --> 58:11.660
Neck.

58:12.060 --> 58:12.860
Very small mouth.

58:13.880 --> 58:14.460
The eyes.

58:15.040 --> 58:15.680
Like this,

58:15.760 --> 58:16.740
as if they were drops.

58:17.400 --> 58:17.920
Like that.

58:19.340 --> 58:19.940
Lilac.

58:20.960 --> 58:22.480
And very peaceful.

58:22.940 --> 58:23.940
There was no suffering there.

58:24.040 --> 58:24.920
No suffering at all.

58:25.960 --> 58:27.580
There was no bad smell.

58:27.940 --> 58:28.480
No odor.

58:28.700 --> 58:30.360
No nervousness.

58:30.780 --> 58:31.700
Nothing diabolical.

58:31.960 --> 58:32.840
A very angelic

58:32.840 --> 58:33.500
kind of being.

58:33.800 --> 58:34.700
Totally at peace.

58:35.300 --> 58:36.680
It's hard to overstate

58:36.680 --> 58:37.520
how bizarre

58:37.520 --> 58:38.740
this must have been.

58:39.020 --> 58:39.700
A neurosurgeon

58:39.700 --> 58:40.360
walking into

58:40.360 --> 58:41.100
what should be

58:41.100 --> 58:42.580
an average day at work

58:42.580 --> 58:43.720
only to find

58:43.720 --> 58:44.360
what looks like

58:44.360 --> 58:45.500
an alien creature

58:45.500 --> 58:47.600
lying in a hospital bed.

58:47.820 --> 58:48.800
It's not bleeding.

58:49.220 --> 58:50.380
It's not in pain.

58:51.080 --> 58:52.240
It's breathing normally.

58:53.080 --> 58:53.900
No problem.

58:55.200 --> 58:56.020
Everything's fine.

58:57.700 --> 58:59.180
The being looked at me.

58:59.820 --> 59:01.040
As I always say,

59:01.040 --> 59:01.960
it looked at me

59:01.960 --> 59:03.500
with a very beautiful look.

59:04.040 --> 59:05.640
Not a judgmental look.

59:05.640 --> 59:07.340
Not a look of fear.

59:08.260 --> 59:09.640
It had the look of someone

59:09.640 --> 59:11.540
who understands very well

59:11.540 --> 59:12.520
what is going on.

59:13.640 --> 59:15.380
But it was a different person.

59:15.540 --> 59:16.320
A different being.

59:16.940 --> 59:18.140
It wasn't human at all.

59:19.000 --> 59:19.920
It wasn't

59:19.920 --> 59:21.620
a case of human anomalies.

59:21.800 --> 59:22.680
It was a different being.

59:23.580 --> 59:25.080
I've been dealing with humans

59:25.080 --> 59:27.460
for 46 years.

59:27.600 --> 59:28.440
But back then,

59:28.500 --> 59:29.460
about 30 years ago,

59:29.460 --> 59:30.660
we knew how to tell

59:30.660 --> 59:31.260
when it was

59:31.260 --> 59:32.160
or wasn't a human.

59:34.620 --> 59:35.720
What's intriguing

59:35.720 --> 59:36.960
is that

59:36.960 --> 59:38.240
they didn't lead

59:38.240 --> 59:39.720
to the initiative,

59:40.060 --> 59:40.680
for example,

59:41.720 --> 59:42.700
of submitting

59:42.700 --> 59:45.080
those who witnessed

59:45.080 --> 59:45.740
the events,

59:46.920 --> 59:47.780
both in the medical

59:47.780 --> 59:49.240
and military fields,

59:51.080 --> 59:52.860
to be questioned,

59:53.940 --> 59:54.580
to help

59:54.580 --> 59:56.360
shine a light

59:56.360 --> 59:57.980
on that event

59:57.980 --> 59:58.860
and

59:58.860 --> 01:00:00.380
maybe lead

01:00:00.380 --> 01:00:01.500
to potential hypotheses

01:00:01.500 --> 01:00:02.320
about

01:00:02.320 --> 01:00:03.840
what was seen,

01:00:04.300 --> 01:00:05.160
about what was

01:00:05.160 --> 01:00:05.940
witnessed,

01:00:05.940 --> 01:00:07.900
what it meant

01:00:07.900 --> 01:00:09.420
and

01:00:09.420 --> 01:00:11.120
the possible origins.

01:00:11.820 --> 01:00:12.100
No,

01:00:12.380 --> 01:00:13.520
they hid it under a rock,

01:00:13.580 --> 01:00:14.080
so to speak.

01:00:15.860 --> 01:00:17.360
The problem was treated

01:00:17.360 --> 01:00:18.700
with a lot of

01:00:18.700 --> 01:00:19.480
secrecy

01:00:19.480 --> 01:00:21.060
and they didn't

01:00:21.060 --> 01:00:22.780
move forward with it.

01:00:23.440 --> 01:00:24.000
The possibility

01:00:24.000 --> 01:00:25.240
to clarify what happened

01:00:25.240 --> 01:00:26.140
never took place,

01:00:26.340 --> 01:00:27.380
except for

01:00:27.380 --> 01:00:29.160
the city of Varginha itself,

01:00:29.300 --> 01:00:30.700
which turned into

01:00:30.700 --> 01:00:31.820
a sort of reference,

01:00:32.740 --> 01:00:33.660
touristically speaking.

01:00:34.360 --> 01:00:34.940
The town hall

01:00:34.940 --> 01:00:36.060
created a museum

01:00:36.060 --> 01:00:38.620
to acknowledge

01:00:38.620 --> 01:00:40.040
and value

01:00:40.040 --> 01:00:41.580
the phenomenon,

01:00:42.300 --> 01:00:43.240
to document it

01:00:43.240 --> 01:00:44.720
and to give it

01:00:44.720 --> 01:00:46.360
a sense of permanence,

01:00:47.020 --> 01:00:47.900
to take it away

01:00:47.900 --> 01:00:48.960
from the world

01:00:48.960 --> 01:00:49.660
of fantasy

01:00:49.660 --> 01:00:50.640
and turn it

01:00:50.640 --> 01:00:51.280
into something,

01:00:52.280 --> 01:00:52.780
a phenomenon

01:00:52.780 --> 01:00:54.120
that was part

01:00:54.120 --> 01:00:55.240
of the town's history,

01:00:55.540 --> 01:00:56.520
the region's history,

01:00:56.920 --> 01:00:58.300
here in the south

01:00:58.300 --> 01:00:59.080
of Minas Gerais.

01:00:59.220 --> 01:00:59.700
By the way,

01:01:00.040 --> 01:01:00.660
the town

01:01:00.660 --> 01:01:01.720
is next door

01:01:01.720 --> 01:01:03.040
to international

